# Instructions
Input format:
One line string message

The string may contain letters, spaces, punctuation.

Only ! and ? are considered as urgency punctuation.

Type exit to terminate the program.

Output:

The program prints:

Number of uppercase letters

Number of punctuation marks (! and ?)

Caps ratio (uppercase / alphabetic characters)

Classification: CALM / URGENT / AGGRESSIVE

Whether there exists a character repeated more than 3 consecutive times

Classification Rules:

AGGRESSIVE

capsRatio ≥ 0.6
OR

punctuation ≥ 5

URGENT

capsRatio ≥ 0.3
OR

punctuation ≥ 3

CALM

Otherwise

Examples
Example 1

Input:

HELLO!!!

Output:

Uppercase: 5
Punctuation: 3
Caps ratio: 1.00
Classification: AGGRESSIVE
Repeat>3: false



#  Brief description of each solution

## Solution of exercise1_content_feed_navigation_with_doubly_linked_list.py
In this exercise, we implemented a browsable content feed using a doubly linked list. 
Each element of the feed is represented by a StoryNode, which stores information such as the story ID, user ID, a short content preview, timestamp, view count, and pointers to the previous and next stories. 
The doubly linked list structure allows efficient navigation in both directions, which is useful for applications such as social media feeds where users may move forward and backward through stories.

Several core operations were implemented, including adding a new story to the feed, removing a story by its ID, 
navigating forward or backward through the stories, jumping directly to a specific story, 
inserting a story after another one, and displaying a range of stories around the current one.




---

## Solution of exercise2

In this exercise, we implemented an activity feed processing system using two fundamental linear data structures: a stack and a queue.
The goal is to simulate how a social platform manages recent user activities and incoming notifications.

The recent activity history is implemented as a pointer-based stack, where each node stores a user action such as like, comment, share, or follow.
Because a stack follows the Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) principle, the most recent activity is always accessed first.
Core operations include pushing a new activity, popping the most recent activity, peeking at the latest action without removing it, and undoing the last action.

The notification system is implemented as a pointer-based queue.
Each node represents a notification, and the queue follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO) rule so that the oldest notification is processed first.
Key operations include enqueueing a new notification, dequeueing the oldest notification, checking the front element, and inserting urgent notifications at the front using a priority enqueue mechanism.

Finally, both structures are integrated into a FeedProcessor system.
This component coordinates the interaction between recent activities and incoming notifications.
Notifications can be transferred from the queue into the activity stack, processed in batches, or moved to a processed log when the activity history is cleared.

The implementation is written in Java, using pointer-style node references to represent dynamic linked data structures.
_
## Solution of exercise3_engagement_based_priority_queue
This solution implements a priority queue of posts using a sorted singly linked list. Posts are ordered by engagement_score in descending order, so the highest-priority post is always at the head. It supports insertion, removal, score update, top-k retrieval, and decay for old posts, which matches the requirements of the exercise.

---

# Complexity analysis summary

## Complexity of exercise1_content_feed_navigation_with_doubly_linked_list.py

add_story(node)
This function adds a new story at the end of the list. Time complexity: O(1)

remove_story(story_id)
This function removes a story by its identifier. Time complexity: O(n)

move_forward()
This function moves current to the next story. Time complexity: O(1)

move_backward()
This function moves current to the previous story. Time complexity: O(1)

jump_to(story_id)
This function moves current to a specific story.Time complexity: O(n)

insert_after(current_id, new_story)
This function inserts a new story after a given story.Time complexity: O(n)

display_around_current(k)
This function displays up to k stories before and after the current story. Time complexity: O(k)

track_view()
This function increments the view count of the current story. Time complexity: O(1)

most_viewed()
This function returns the story with the highest number of views. Time complexity: O(n)

reorder_by_views()
This function reorganizes the feed so that the most viewed stories appear first. Time complexity: O(n²)


---

## Complexity of exercise2

Complexity of exercise2_activity_feed_processing_with_stacks_and_queues

Stack Operations (Recent Activity)

push(activity): O(1)
A new node is inserted at the top of the stack.

pop(): O(1)
The top node is removed and returned.

peek(): O(1)
The algorithm directly reads the value of the top node.

is_empty(): O(1)
It checks whether the top pointer is NULL.

size(): O(1)
The stack maintains a counter of elements.

display_recent(n): O(n)
The algorithm traverses up to n nodes starting from the top.

undo_last(): O(1)
It removes the top element and pushes it into the undo stack.

Queue Operations (Notification Queue)

enqueue(notification): O(1)
The new notification is added at the rear of the queue.

dequeue(): O(1)
The front node is removed and returned.

priority_enqueue(notification): O(1)
An urgent notification is inserted at the front of the queue.

front(): O(1)
The algorithm directly accesses the front node.

is_empty(): O(1)
It checks whether the front pointer is NULL.

size(): O(1)
The queue maintains a counter of elements.

display_pending(): O(n)
The queue is traversed from front to rear.

FeedProcessor Operations

process_incoming(): O(1)
One notification is dequeued and pushed into the activity stack.

batch_process(k): O(k)
The algorithm processes the first k notifications in the queue.

clear_history(): O(n)
All activities in the stack are popped and inserted into the processed log.

get_stats(): O(1)
The function simply returns the sizes of the three structures.

Space Complexity

Space Complexity: O(n)

The system stores activities and notifications using linked nodes.
Each node contains the data and a pointer to the next node, so the memory usage grows linearly with the number of elements.

## Complexity of exercise3_engagement_based_priority_queue
For Time Complexity :

enqueue(post): O(n)
The list must be traversed to find the correct insertion position to maintain descending order of engagement_score.

dequeue_max(): O(1)
The highest-priority post is always at the head of the list, so removal is constant time.

peek_max(): O(1)
The head node already stores the maximum priority element.

is_empty(): O(1)
It only checks whether the head pointer is NULL.

size(): O(1)
The queue maintains a counter of the number of posts.

update_score(post_id, ...): O(n)
The algorithm must traverse the list to find the post (O(n)) and then reinsert it in sorted order (O(n)), but overall complexity remains O(n).

refresh_all(): O(n²)
Each post is removed and reinserted into a new sorted queue, and each insertion costs up to O(n).

get_top_k(k): O(k)
The algorithm traverses the first k nodes of the list.

decay_older_than(timestamp): O(n²)
It first scans all posts (O(n)) and then calls refresh_all() which re-sorts the queue.

Space Complexity

Space Complexity: O(n)
The queue stores n posts in a linked list. Each node contains the post data and a next pointer.


